After moving `vscode-go` from applying full-document-replacement edits to [applying multiple targeted edits for formatting](https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode-go/pull/111), I'm seeing one odd case.

When the formatter asks to replace 4 spaces with a tab, we compute the two edits below:

``` json
[
 {
  "_range": {
   "_start": {
    "_line": 3,
    "_character": 0
   },
   "_end": {
    "_line": 3,
    "_character": 4
   }
  },
  "_newText": ""
 },
 {
  "_range": {
   "_start": {
    "_line": 3,
    "_character": 4
   },
   "_end": {
    "_line": 3,
    "_character": 4
   }
  },
  "_newText": "\t"
 }
]
```

But when we return these edits, they do not get applied.  Worse, if these edits are part of a set of 20 edits, none of the edits get applied.  And worse, we get no error returned to us or reported to the user about these edits being invalid.

Is this an illegal edit, and if so why?

Is it expected that we don't get any feedback about the edits being incorrect?

/cc @newhook

I wants to use vscode as my git-cli editor. So I need an option that the calling process get stoped until the file I want to edit is closed.

I modified the bin\code.js in this form:

``` javascript
delete process.env['ATOM_SHELL_INTERNAL_RUN_AS_NODE'];
require('child_process')
    .spawn(require('path').resolve(__dirname, '..', 'Code.exe'), process.argv.slice(2), {
        detached: true,
        stdio: 'ignore'
    })
    .on('close', process.exit);
if (process.argv.indexOf('-w')===-1&&process.argv.indexOf('--wait')===-1) {process.exit(0);}
```

But it only works if there are no other arguments and vscode is not already open.

